<font color="#FF0000">A STORY</font><br>
<tt>Mon Feb 24  2:09:39 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
This feels a little weird. But here it is. Word for Word fm about 1986:<br><br>
&quot;The passing of 20 years has modified the perspective of <br>
most memories. Most, not all. In 1965 the War was small and<br>
remote. It was impersonal and academic, at most a curiosity<br>
intensely reported on the evening new. As arrogant young<br>
college students, we debated its morality and politics. Too<br>
much was happening here for Nam to alter the tide. Hell, <br>
most conversation centered on sex, football, music, and sex.<br>
Occasionally the ripple effect of a brother or old buddy<br>
who was on his way home in one of those chilly silver boxes<br>
would impose itself upon us. Still we felt secure, insulated<br>
and unafraid. WE were destined for greater things.<br><br>
Those early memories are filtered as are most memories. The<br>
experiments with pot, the academics, a generations emerging<br>
musical signature and social activism are all even nostalgic<br>
now. Not so the Nam. There was the misery, fear, and horror<br>
of the smell of it. The sound of a rocket and how the blast<br>
seemed to penetrate into your depths linger. The vision of<br>
humans ripped apart like a Friday the 13th special effect<br>
are impressed like photo negatives in your brain. Clear and<br>
unadulterated.<br><br>
People speak of how our generation has seemed unable to cope<br>
with the experience. Talk about an emergence from childhood.<br>
WE lulled ourselves into thinking our generation would<br>
see space and beyond. WE would face racial equality and win.<br>
And in retrospect, WE would see the world come around to our<br>
way of thinking. The Nam was total trauma. It would have so<br>
much better if we had stayed steeped in bigotry or been a <br>
new generation of immigrants. Steeled by struggle. At least<br>
they were determined not optimistic.<br><br>
Then came October of 1966 and a draft notice. We were only <br>
mildly stunned. We thought there might be a way out. But<br>
reality marched in. Induction in December. We questioned it<br>
but all be few considered escape. The first chill set in. <br><br>
Control was no longer yours. Deep down we were all afraid,<br>
but we didn't discuss it. The cruelty of wartime basic<br>
training was stunning. In short order, resistance was an<br>
act of futility. Like the generations before us, we simply<br>
got into it as best we could. We became heartbreakers and<br>
killers. The cadences echo in my memory, &quot;I wonna be an<br>
Airborne Ranger.....,  I don't know but I've been told....<br>
Ho Chi Minh is a son of a bitch&quot;. Many broke and simply<br>
dissappeared. I suspect we had more wash out than other<br>
generations due to our idealism and rebelious attitude<br>
toward Norms. But no matter how hard we tried, our generation ended up different.<br><br>
Maybe if the Nam had been more like conventional wars. You<br>
know, DDays, Shiloh, Battle of the Bulge. Clear Victory or<br>
Defeat. The Nam was a suffer and die machine. Always had<br>
been and always would be. Help the little people, and watch<br>
Charlie slaughter them. Help the Villagers and watch them<br>
gratefully snipe at you or booby trap you trails. Free fire<br>
zones, and search and destroy. Evil jungled little hills<br>
laced with tunnels and the pointless mission of take and <br>
retake. Those miserable nights in the bush waiting to kill<br>
or be killed. Who are these people and what am I doing <br>
here?<br><br>
Be assured we lost more than previous generations. We<br>
carried far too much idealistic luggage. We will forever pay<br>
the price. We still retain our rebellion, and I wonder in how many middle aged homes, a joint is passed around to the<br>
pounding of Uriah Heep or Pink Floyd?<br><br>
How does a person erase it and leave it behind? Can you <br>
remember the BS of basic and then being processed in <br>
Country? That isolated feeling of being an FNG? Rapidly the<br>
shit piled up higher and deeper. The killing began. Finally<br>
desparately hanging on and hoping to survive with just all<br>
your body parts. Just writing these words, I feel that<br>
gnawing feeling in my guts. Like I'm back there. Hell, I'm<br>
there already.<br><br>
The patrol had been miserable, but routine. Then someone<br>
whispered bunker, and the shit began. First an explosion<br>
to our right, and then the fire. The sound was bad enough,<br>
but when someone fell, it hit you. A rocket hit within<br>
20 yards of us, and we went down. I remember sitting up and<br>
my ears were stopped up. Then I saw Larry. He was no more<br>
than 15 feet from where I sat. His hip and lower body were<br>
ripped apart. He feebly reached down and died. Blood burned<br>
my eyes, and I remember sitting up and wretching. I never<br>
knew I could throw up and still hold my weapon and scan the<br>
area for enemy. I thought I was going to die. I didn't.<br><br>
They got us out a day later. A second rocket tore us up a<br>
bit but we were evacuated out and lived. We were lucky. I<br>
went from a year and a half of it to Germany.<br><br>
The 70's were a time of trying to get on with life. Hard work and a child and dealing with nagging scars. I never wanted anyone to know how often there were sleepless nights. There were moments at work, when someone would enter my office and jerk me out of a reverie that the clock would show had lasted 30 minutes. They would wonder about the<br>
sweat and I would talk about that virus that was going<br>
around. There were the nights of drinking into a stupor in<br>
order to sleep. The episodes of waking up screaming, that<br>
so frightened by wife and boy. Finally joining a group of<br>
Vets who showed you that you weren't alone. Such a relief.<br>
Understanding that the memories don't fade. They just <br>
become normal. Eventually meeting and telling friends that<br>
this happens and having them support you instead of moving<br>
away.<br><br>
There are some things of which I am certain. The Nam<br>
irrevocably altered who I am. A compromise was struck in<br>
that place that I never wanted. A deal with the Devil, one<br>
you can't win. I thought I was just doing what everyone<br>
should do for his country. Naive. Instead, I had sold my<br>
soul. Hell, you don't even know it till later. The dreams<br>
and tears tell you then.<br><br>
Our friends try to give us support. But no one can give you<br>
an explanation of why you got to see and participate in the<br>
gore that is War. It is real. It's like DNA. Once you are<br>
created in it, it is as real every day of your life as your<br>
skin. Yeah, the wrong generation at the wrong place, at the<br>
wrong time, with the wrong leaders. It happens. You had to<br>
live the 60's to understand the times and how it was.<br><br>
Strange events still sneak up on me. I've always enjoyed<br>
hunting. I love the forest and nature. I didn't hunt much<br>
after the Nam. That joy didn't feel right anymore. It <br>
surprised me when some friends invited me to a deer hunt<br>
and I totally liked it. The next year when we went, I went<br>
out the first morning, and when the sun rose, the reports<br>
of the rifles rang through the woods. I was sitting against<br>
a tree at the edge of a stand of trees. It was warm and wet.<br>
I saw a shadow move to my right. I frooze. I was back there<br>
again. A chill went up my spine. It was overpowering. I<br>
crouched even more, afraid to breath. I knew my reflexes<br>
were wired, ready to react. After about thirty minutes,<br>
I was able to relax. Oddly, I leaned against the tree and<br>
fell asleep. When I awoke, I began to move to camp, but<br>
it hadn't left me. I moved carefully. Quick then slow. I<br>
watched for trip wires. I could feel Charlie's eyes on me.<br>
My mind said, &quot;your're hunting in Texas&quot;. My body wouldn't<br>
listen. In camp, no one asked why I was so quiet and stayed<br>
out of conversation range.<br><br>
I don't feel sorry for myself. The bonds I made in Nam are<br>
like none other so far. I have a good job. I love my kid.<br>
I know plenty of Vets not so lucky. Many are still on point.<br><br>
Two months ago I got a phone call from West Virginia. It was<br>
a young man who had recently read a bunch of letters his Dad<br>
had written home from Nam. He had never come home. It was<br>
Larry's kid.<br><br>
Larry and I had been through basic and AIT together, and<br>
then the Nam. Evidently Larry had mentioned me in one of the<br>
letters. The kid had tracked me down. He was 23 years old<br>
like my boy, and had visited the Wall in Washington a few<br>
months before. The experience had motivated him to contact<br>
some of us. He said he didn't remember Larry, since he was<br>
only 2 when he died. But when he read the letters, it made<br>
him think of his Dad he didn't know. When he read some of<br>
the passages from the letters, my tears came. I tried to<br>
explain some of the things that happened to us. Right in the<br>
middle of it, I remembered that patrol coming back in. I<br>
remembered that we didn't have a body bag for Larry, and<br>
brought him in on a poncho. What was left of him. I told him<br>
Larry was a good ole boy. He would have made a fine Father.<br>
Our conversation slowly faded away. I got screaming drunk<br>
that night and saluted my friends. I miss them.<br><br>
I'm not sure why I have written this. Sometimes it seems I<br>
have to talk. Vietnam means something to America. As the<br>
years pass, those of us who remember the hills and jungle<br>
trails grow fewer and fewer. Soon none will be left. Somehow<br>
I know that as I become more and more of a relic, I will<br>
feel more and more lonely. It's as if the life I've lived<br>
out of the Nam was an afterthought. How strange to feel <br>
that. I pray that as long as I can talk, there will be <br>
someone out there who will listen and care. I don't want<br>
to feel left over there again, when no one cared. Not<br>
again.<br><br>
Maybe I'll let some of my friends read this.&quot;<br><br>
Well there it is.<br><br>
I'm, back in the world.<br><br>
See ya,<br><br>
 
<p><code>-- carnival@ ont.com  (JJ the Boonirat) </code><p>


